statistically significant.

00:41:20.150 --> 00:41:21.445
And he went nuts.

00:41:21.445 --> 00:41:23.590
Sorry to tell you this.

00:41:23.590 --> 00:41:27.190
So I think it remains to be seen
whether there is indeed a

00:41:27.190 --> 00:41:29.335
Coriolis effect in
crystal shapes.

00:41:29.335 --> 00:41:29.970
And that's true.

00:41:29.970 --> 00:41:30.760
It's tragic.

00:41:30.760 --> 00:41:33.410
We're all laughing
at the poor guy.

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:36.060
But he actually just
couldn't stand it.

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:39.470
He counted so many
crystals, poof!

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:45.820
That's a true, unfortunate
story.

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:49.400
No, I don't think there is any
difference between left handed

00:41:49.400 --> 00:41:53.000
crystals or right
handed crystals.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:57.640
Remember my story about sugar
and its chirality and the

00:41:57.640 --> 00:42:01.610
little bugs that can only
eat one chirality.

00:42:01.610 --> 00:42:04.980
Other questions of the less
frivolous nature?

00:42:04.980 --> 00:42:05.420
That was not frivolous.

00:42:05.420 --> 00:42:06.670
That was a good question.

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:11.490
OK, well let's say a little bit
about glide planes and how

00:42:11.490 --> 00:42:13.500
they appear in space groups.

00:42:16.330 --> 00:42:20.140
Things were very easy in two
dimensions because the glide

00:42:20.140 --> 00:42:22.930
plane was a glide line.

00:42:22.930 --> 00:42:26.470
And everything had to
be confined to a

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:28.150
two dimensional space.

00:42:28.150 --> 00:42:32.970
So we used a solid line to
indicate a mirror plane, the

00:42:32.970 --> 00:42:34.740
locus of the operation, sigma.

00:42:34.740 --> 00:42:37.980
And we use a dashed line to
indicate the locus of an

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:39.900
operation, sigma tau.

00:42:39.900 --> 00:42:44.510
And tau was in the direction
of the dashes.

00:42:44.510 --> 00:42:46.930
Well, I've given it all away
with the little diagram that I

00:42:46.930 --> 00:42:47.550
passed around.

00:42:47.550 --> 00:42:49.900
Things are much more complicated
in three

00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:50.540
dimensions.

00:42:50.540 --> 00:42:53.670
If this is the locus of a glide
plane and this is the

00:42:53.670 --> 00:42:58.500
direction of tau in a space
group, we could be looking at

00:42:58.500 --> 00:43:04.570
that glide plane in a total
of four different ways.

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:07.780
We could be looking at the glide
plane from the side,

00:43:07.780 --> 00:43:11.090
edge on, and perpendicular
to tau.

00:43:11.090 --> 00:43:15.460
We could be looking at the glide
plane edge on and along

00:43:15.460 --> 00:43:17.230
the direction of tau.

00:43:17.230 --> 00:43:21.170
Or we could be between these two
orientations and looking

00:43:21.170 --> 00:43:25.290
at the glide plane edge on but
in between normal to tau and

00:43:25.290 --> 00:43:27.690
parallel to tau.

00:43:27.690 --> 00:43:30.310
And finally, we could look
at the glide plane

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:31.560
down from the top.

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:38.270
If we view the glide plane
from above, for example

00:43:38.270 --> 00:43:42.040
suppose we have a monoclinic
crystal and we put a glide

00:43:42.040 --> 00:43:45.040
plane in the base of the cell
which has tau in this

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:48.250
direction, the way you indicate
that is with a little

00:43:48.250 --> 00:43:50.610
chevron off to the side.

00:43:50.610 --> 00:43:54.560
And if this is the direction of
tau, you put a little barb

00:43:54.560 --> 00:43:58.830
on the chevron that indicates
the direction of tau.

00:43:58.830 --> 00:44:03.200
So the three possibilities for
a monoclinic crystal is that

00:44:03.200 --> 00:44:06.020
how could be this way, in
which case you use a

00:44:06.020 --> 00:44:07.610
chevron like this.

00:44:07.610 --> 00:44:11.660
Or how could be in
this direction.

00:44:11.660 --> 00:44:13.817
And then, you use a chevron
with a barb

00:44:13.817 --> 00:44:15.660
attached like this.

00:44:15.660 --> 00:44:21.310
Or how could be a diagonal
glide, in which case the atoms

00:44:21.310 --> 00:44:25.040
would be up and opposite
chirality and

00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:28.010
down and back up again.

00:44:28.010 --> 00:44:33.000
In that case, you add a little
barb in between the two

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:39.550
directions to indicate
the direction of tau.

00:44:39.550 --> 00:44:44.280
We put some labels on this,
this a and this b.

00:44:44.280 --> 00:44:49.250
This situation would be a tau
that is equal to 1/2 of b.

00:44:49.250 --> 00:44:54.300
In this case, how would
be equal to 1/2 of a.

00:44:54.300 --> 00:45:00.580
In this case, how would be
equal to 1/2 of a plus b.

00:45:04.180 --> 00:45:10.140
This is designated
as a b glide.

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:14.060
And rather than having the
symbol n appear in the symbol

00:45:14.060 --> 00:45:16.800
for the space group,
a b would appear.

00:45:16.800 --> 00:45:18.260
This is an a glide.

00:45:21.100 --> 00:45:24.510
And the a would appear
in the symbol.

00:45:24.510 --> 00:45:26.695
And this is a diagonal glide.

00:45:32.620 --> 00:45:36.780
And that, for reasons that I
have never found anyone able

00:45:36.780 --> 00:45:40.600
to explain to me, is
called an n glide.

00:45:40.600 --> 00:45:44.065
I know of no language in which
the word for diagonal

00:45:44.065 --> 00:45:45.315
begins with an n.

00:45:47.460 --> 00:45:48.710
But that's what it's called.

00:45:50.850 --> 00:45:54.120
Now, those same glides can be
viewed from directions that

00:45:54.120 --> 00:45:57.110
are parallel to the plane
of the glide plane.

00:45:57.110 --> 00:46:01.020
Looking normal to tau is exactly
the same situation we

00:46:01.020 --> 00:46:03.190
had in plane groups.

00:46:03.190 --> 00:46:05.710
So one uses the dash.

00:46:05.710 --> 00:46:08.620
If you're looking along the
glide plane end on but in the

00:46:08.620 --> 00:46:13.140
direction of tau, you
use a dotted line.

00:46:13.140 --> 00:46:14.850
It's easy to keep straight
which is which.

00:46:14.850 --> 00:46:16.800
If there's a little arrow in
there and you look at it from

00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:18.300
the side, you see
a line segment.

00:46:18.300 --> 00:46:20.780
If you look at it from the
end, you see a dot.

00:46:20.780 --> 00:46:24.340
So it's easy to remember
this convention.

00:46:24.340 --> 00:46:26.900
If you're neither perpendicular
to nor parallel

00:46:26.900 --> 00:46:30.080
to the glide plane, you just
mix the two symbols.

00:46:30.080 --> 00:46:31.690
So you use a dashed dot line.

00:46:35.540 --> 00:46:39.830
So those are the symbols
for glide.

00:46:39.830 --> 00:46:42.460
Glide plane is something
like a piece of wood.

00:46:42.460 --> 00:46:44.240
It's got grain to it.

00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:46.950
The direction of the grain
is the direction of

00:46:46.950 --> 00:46:48.200
tau, if you'd like.

00:46:52.460 --> 00:46:59.050
All right, in the hand out, I
give you some examples of the

00:46:59.050 --> 00:47:02.620
way in which a pattern of
objects that has glide in it

00:47:02.620 --> 00:47:07.780
would be interpreted in terms
of a geometric symbol.

00:47:07.780 --> 00:47:11.040
At the bottom right of the page,
the left hand diagram

00:47:11.040 --> 00:47:15.550
has atoms related by a glide
plane in the base of the cell

00:47:15.550 --> 00:47:18.920
where tau is running
left to right.

00:47:18.920 --> 00:47:21.800
And so you have a chevron
with an arrow on

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:24.400
the right hand branch.

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:29.400
If you have atoms alternately
left handed, right handed at a

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:33.140
level and 1/2 plus that
elevation, then you're looking

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:35.840
at a glide plane edge on
and down along the

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:37.060
direction of tau.

00:47:37.060 --> 00:47:40.200
So you would indicate the locus
of that glide plane by a

00:47:40.200 --> 00:47:41.500
series of dots.

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:53.150
What other type of glide plane
is possible, not for

00:47:53.150 --> 00:48:08.330
monoclinic, but for lattices
that have a centered lattice

00:48:08.330 --> 00:48:10.480
point in the middle
of the cell?

00:48:16.890 --> 00:48:19.480
So this takes a special type
of Bravais lattice.

00:48:23.610 --> 00:48:29.900
And this would be a lattice, for
example, that had lattice

00:48:29.900 --> 00:48:33.210
points at the corners of the
cell and another lattice point

00:48:33.210 --> 00:48:35.080
in the middle of the cell.

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:36.960
One face of the cell
is centered.

00:48:36.960 --> 00:48:41.860
Then, you have not only
translations a, b, and a plus

00:48:41.860 --> 00:48:47.080
b, which can serve as directions
for glide.

00:48:47.080 --> 00:48:49.890
But you have another translation
that is not

00:48:49.890 --> 00:48:51.540
present in the primitive
lattice.

00:48:51.540 --> 00:48:58.090
And this is 1/2 of
a plus 1/2 of b.

00:48:58.090 --> 00:49:01.500
And if that's a translation, you
could have a glide plane

00:49:01.500 --> 00:49:06.545
parallel to the base of the cell
and have tau equal to 1/2

00:49:06.545 --> 00:49:10.955
of 1/2 of a plus b, namely have
this little vector in

00:49:10.955 --> 00:49:13.830
here be tau.

00:49:13.830 --> 00:49:17.340
And the symbol for that
kind of glide is d.

00:49:17.340 --> 00:49:19.270
And I do know what
that stands for.

00:49:19.270 --> 00:49:24.160
That stands for a diamond glide
because diamond, one of

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:29.030
the very simple structures for
an element or any compound and

00:49:29.030 --> 00:49:33.990
one of the early structures to
be determined experimentally,

00:49:33.990 --> 00:49:36.110
does have a d glide in it.

00:49:36.110 --> 00:49:39.310
So the name of the compound,
diamond, gave its name to the

00:49:39.310 --> 00:49:40.560
type of glide plane.

00:49:51.540 --> 00:49:53.770
OK, I've got still
10 more minutes.

00:49:53.770 --> 00:49:58.610
What I would like to do next
is to look at some of the

00:49:58.610 --> 00:50:03.810
other monoclinic space groups
and also examine the way in

00:50:03.810 --> 00:50:06.730
which this information is
presented for you in the

00:50:06.730 --> 00:50:09.320
international tables.

00:50:09.320 --> 00:50:14.580
So I've got a big, fat pack of
material that shows you all of

00:50:14.580 --> 00:50:17.210
the monoclinic space group,
that is the space groups

00:50:17.210 --> 00:50:21.510
derived from point group two,
the space groups with point

00:50:21.510 --> 00:50:24.970
group m, and the space groups
with point group 2/m.

00:50:30.400 --> 00:50:31.620
And we've done a few of these.

00:50:31.620 --> 00:50:36.020
But what we haven't looked at
is the Shcoenflies notation

00:50:36.020 --> 00:50:41.610
for the result or the way in
which this information is

00:50:41.610 --> 00:50:45.005
presented in the international
tables.

00:50:48.520 --> 00:50:52.990
To introduce you to these
gradually, this is the

00:50:52.990 --> 00:50:54.570
monoclinic space group--

00:50:54.570 --> 00:50:57.940
these are the monoclinic space
groups as presented in the old

00:50:57.940 --> 00:51:01.430
international tables for
x-ray crystallography.

00:51:01.430 --> 00:51:05.360
A little bit later, I will pass
out to you a few higher

00:51:05.360 --> 00:51:11.690
symmetry space groups that are
represented in both the old

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:15.100
international tables and the
new international tables.

00:51:15.100 --> 00:51:18.780
And as I indicated somewhat
disparagingly earlier on,

00:51:18.780 --> 00:51:21.920
there is so much information
in the new version that

00:51:21.920 --> 00:51:24.860
they're very, very
hard to use.

00:51:24.860 --> 00:51:33.070
But OK, if you open the hand
out, you find space group P2.

00:51:33.070 --> 00:51:35.160
So that's a twofold
axis added to a

00:51:35.160 --> 00:51:36.600
primitive monoclinic axis.

00:51:39.850 --> 00:51:44.440
You see on the left hand page
this situation, this

00:51:44.440 --> 00:51:47.790
ridiculous situation, that
exists only for monoclinic

00:51:47.790 --> 00:51:53.920
crystals the first setting,
where the axes are a on the

00:51:53.920 --> 00:51:57.020
left hand side running down, and
b on the top running from

00:51:57.020 --> 00:51:59.970
left to right, and c coming
straight up out of the page.

00:51:59.970 --> 00:52:08.110
And the second setting, where
the unique axis is b, and that

00:52:08.110 --> 00:52:12.880
means if you're going to draw
the space group with c coming

00:52:12.880 --> 00:52:18.460
up, a down, and b to the right,
b now is the direction

00:52:18.460 --> 00:52:19.450
of the twofold axis.

00:52:19.450 --> 00:52:22.100
So the diagram looks completely
different.

00:52:22.100 --> 00:52:27.770
But it's the same space group
except that the first setting

00:52:27.770 --> 00:52:33.050
is tilted on its side so that
a comes down, b is from left

00:52:33.050 --> 00:52:37.390
to right, and c, which is now
not a direction of the twofold

00:52:37.390 --> 00:52:39.010
axis, comes out.

00:52:39.010 --> 00:52:44.060
So there's some jargon here,
that geometric jargon.

00:52:44.060 --> 00:52:47.300
The atoms occur at different
elevations.

00:52:47.300 --> 00:52:52.190
So in these two cases, the atoms
occur only at elevations

00:52:52.190 --> 00:52:54.490
plus z or minus z.

00:52:54.490 --> 00:52:57.970
And you see next to the little
circles that represent the

00:52:57.970 --> 00:52:59.880
symmetry equivalent
positions for the

00:52:59.880 --> 00:53:01.980
general position a plus.

00:53:01.980 --> 00:53:05.360
And that means elevation
plus z.

00:53:05.360 --> 00:53:08.980
And for the first setting,
all the atoms occur at an

00:53:08.980 --> 00:53:12.170
elevation plus z for the
general position.

00:53:12.170 --> 00:53:14.880
For the second setting in the
right hand diagram, you're

00:53:14.880 --> 00:53:18.090
looking at the twofold
axis from the side.

00:53:18.090 --> 00:53:20.470
And therefore, one atom
is at plus z.

00:53:20.470 --> 00:53:22.940
The one that's related by
symmetry gets rotated

00:53:22.940 --> 00:53:24.080
down to minus z.

00:53:24.080 --> 00:53:27.750
So you see a little plus next
to one atom, a little minus

00:53:27.750 --> 00:53:31.550
next to the next to it.

00:53:31.550 --> 00:53:36.670
We need a symbol for a view
down along the locus of a

00:53:36.670 --> 00:53:37.650
twofold axis.

00:53:37.650 --> 00:53:40.520
And that's the little pointed
oval that we became familiar

00:53:40.520 --> 00:53:42.710
with with the plane groups.

00:53:42.710 --> 00:53:45.800
When you're looking at the
twofold axis from the side,

00:53:45.800 --> 00:53:47.300
how are you going to
indicate that?

00:53:47.300 --> 00:53:50.420
Well, the convention
is to use an arrow.

00:53:50.420 --> 00:53:52.950
And that's what you see on the
right hand side for the second

00:53:52.950 --> 00:53:55.910
setting of P2.

00:53:55.910 --> 00:53:59.990
If this were not a twofold axis
but a 2 sub 1 screw axis,

00:53:59.990 --> 00:54:02.720
it would be a one-sided barb.

00:54:02.720 --> 00:54:09.090
So looking down at these two
axes with rotations of 180

00:54:09.090 --> 00:54:13.020
degrees, this is the symbol for
two viewed from the side.

00:54:13.020 --> 00:54:17.030
And a one-sided barb would
be the symbol for a

00:54:17.030 --> 00:54:19.030
2 sub 1 screw axis.

00:54:19.030 --> 00:54:23.510
Mercifully, these are the only
screw axes that need to be

00:54:23.510 --> 00:54:25.810
depicted in a view
from the side.

00:54:25.810 --> 00:54:30.520
So there's no standard symbol
for a sixfold access or a

00:54:30.520 --> 00:54:32.650
fourfold axis looked
at from the side.

00:54:36.570 --> 00:54:40.240
In boldface, in the outer corner
of these pages, you see

00:54:40.240 --> 00:54:44.590
the international symbol, which
is what we used for the

00:54:44.590 --> 00:54:49.610
plane groups, the symbol for the
lattice type, primitive,

00:54:49.610 --> 00:54:52.970
except now we use uppercase
symbols for the lattice type

00:54:52.970 --> 00:54:56.890
to distinguish the space groups
from the plane groups.

00:54:56.890 --> 00:55:02.590
Underneath it, you see
a C2 superscript 1.

00:55:02.590 --> 00:55:04.560
This is the Schoenflies
symbol.

00:55:04.560 --> 00:55:08.700
You'll recognize C2 as the
Schoenflies symbol for a

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:10.470
twofold axis.

00:55:10.470 --> 00:55:13.580
Schoenflies' symbol for the
space group was to add a

00:55:13.580 --> 00:55:17.240
superscript, namely the first
one that old [? Artur ?]

00:55:17.240 --> 00:55:20.740
got, the second one that
[? Artur ?] got from this

00:55:20.740 --> 00:55:22.720
point group, the third one
he got from the point

00:55:22.720 --> 00:55:23.880
group, and so on.

00:55:23.880 --> 00:55:27.560
So it's pretty much an arbitrary
order, except he

00:55:27.560 --> 00:55:32.140
starts with, as you'll see, a
twofold access, then replaces

00:55:32.140 --> 00:55:36.130
the twofold axis with
a screw access.

00:55:36.130 --> 00:55:40.790
So if you turn to the next page,
you see symbols for not

00:55:40.790 --> 00:55:44.810
twofold axes, but 2 sub
1 screw axes along the

00:55:44.810 --> 00:55:47.040
edges of the cell.

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:51.420
You see now a different sort of
symbol alongside the atoms.

00:55:51.420 --> 00:55:52.720
There's one at plus z.

00:55:52.720 --> 00:55:55.200
That's the representative
one at x, y, z.

00:55:55.200 --> 00:55:58.620
If you repeat it by a screw
rotation, you rotate it 180

00:55:58.620 --> 00:56:02.030
degrees and slide it up
by 1/2 of [? c. ?]

00:56:02.030 --> 00:56:05.320
So you see the symbol
1/2 plus.

00:56:05.320 --> 00:56:06.770
So plus is plus z.

00:56:06.770 --> 00:56:11.580
1/2 plus is 1/2 plus z.

00:56:11.580 --> 00:56:16.630
Over to the second settings,
trying not to sneer too

00:56:16.630 --> 00:56:20.910
vigorously, you'll see
pointed barbs.

00:56:20.910 --> 00:56:22.740
That's the symbol for
a twofold axis

00:56:22.740 --> 00:56:24.100
viewed from the side.

00:56:24.100 --> 00:56:27.950
And then, one of them is plus.

00:56:27.950 --> 00:56:30.990
The one that's a little long
parallel to the 2 sub 1 screw

00:56:30.990 --> 00:56:34.150
axis goes to the other side and
goes from plus z down to

00:56:34.150 --> 00:56:35.400
the minus z.

00:56:38.670 --> 00:56:41.470
Let me ask you a question which
people usually don't

00:56:41.470 --> 00:56:41.950
think about.

00:56:41.950 --> 00:56:44.760
If you look at the first setting
and ask, what are the

00:56:44.760 --> 00:56:48.020
lengths of the translations?

00:56:48.020 --> 00:56:48.505
That's a.

00:56:48.505 --> 00:56:50.100
And that's so many angstroms.

00:56:50.100 --> 00:56:50.780
And that's b.

00:56:50.780 --> 00:56:53.170
That's so many angstroms.

00:56:53.170 --> 00:56:57.180
If I ask you that for the second
setting, the answer is

00:56:57.180 --> 00:56:59.720
a little trickier.

00:56:59.720 --> 00:57:02.170
What is the length of
this translation?

00:57:02.170 --> 00:57:04.540
That's b.

00:57:04.540 --> 00:57:06.960
What is the length of
this translation?

00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:08.120
I'm sorry, that's c.

00:57:08.120 --> 00:57:11.430
And this translation
is a, right?

00:57:11.430 --> 00:57:12.890
Wrong.

00:57:12.890 --> 00:57:15.060
That is no longer a.

00:57:15.060 --> 00:57:21.815
And the reason for that is that
when you have a cell with

00:57:21.815 --> 00:57:27.260
non-orthogonal angles in it, let
me indicate for the most

00:57:27.260 --> 00:57:32.560
general case for a triclinic
crystal.

00:57:32.560 --> 00:57:35.310
So this is a.

00:57:35.310 --> 00:57:37.060
This is b.

00:57:37.060 --> 00:57:41.915
And then the third translation
normal to that plane is c.

00:57:46.040 --> 00:57:51.610
And if we have a structure with
atoms in these locations

00:57:51.610 --> 00:57:56.050
and we want to project the
structure along c, you do

00:57:56.050 --> 00:57:57.340
exactly that.

00:57:57.340 --> 00:58:01.170
You don't plop the atoms down
onto the base of the cell when

00:58:01.170 --> 00:58:07.820
you project it because if you
did so, the atom that is up in

00:58:07.820 --> 00:58:10.470
the neighboring unit cell
would come down

00:58:10.470 --> 00:58:12.980
to a different location.

00:58:12.980 --> 00:58:16.750
And you would not have a pattern
that was periodic

00:58:16.750 --> 00:58:18.640
based on a lattice.

00:58:18.640 --> 00:58:22.580
You get that only if, when
you're projecting in an

00:58:22.580 --> 00:58:27.750
oblique lattice, you project
along the translation.

00:58:27.750 --> 00:58:32.080
And then, and only then, can you
end up with a pattern that

00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:35.320
looks like it has translational
periodicity and

00:58:35.320 --> 00:58:37.640
really does.

00:58:37.640 --> 00:58:40.190
So if a cell is oblique, you
do not project just by

00:58:40.190 --> 00:58:42.680
plopping the atoms down on
the base of the cell.

00:58:42.680 --> 00:58:46.450
You project them parallel to the
translation that extends

00:58:46.450 --> 00:58:50.140
up above the direction onto
which you're projecting.

00:58:50.140 --> 00:59:01.730
So if our cell in the second
setting is monoclinic and this

00:59:01.730 --> 00:59:09.000
is a and this b and c comes up,
if we look at that cell

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:12.960
from the side as is done in
the depiction on the right

00:59:12.960 --> 00:59:17.590
hand, then we let this be
the direction of b.

00:59:17.590 --> 00:59:20.080
So that is b.

00:59:20.080 --> 00:59:29.980
But the thing that is at right
angles to b is going to be a

00:59:29.980 --> 00:59:36.300
times the cosine of beta.

00:59:36.300 --> 00:59:37.696
And it's not a itself.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:42.470
So this is a right angle.

00:59:42.470 --> 00:59:45.900
But this is not the lattice
translation.

00:59:45.900 --> 00:59:49.510
It is the lattice translation
times a

00:59:49.510 --> 00:59:51.570
trigonometric function.

00:59:51.570 --> 00:59:55.350
The triclinic case
is a hairy beast.

00:59:58.150 --> 01:00:01.830
To calculate the length of these
axes and projection,

01:00:01.830 --> 01:00:03.910
it's clear what they are.

01:00:03.910 --> 01:00:07.210
But to get these values
involves alpha

01:00:07.210 --> 01:00:09.040
and beta and gamma.

01:00:09.040 --> 01:00:11.950
And it's a very, very
complicated function.

01:00:14.842 --> 01:00:17.975
AUDIENCE: So the angle between
a and c in general is not 90

01:00:17.975 --> 01:00:19.670
degrees in monoclinics?

01:00:19.670 --> 01:00:21.850
PROFESSOR: The angle between
depends on how

01:00:21.850 --> 01:00:22.970
you label your axes.

01:00:22.970 --> 01:00:25.970
For monoclinic, if you do the
first setting, then by

01:00:25.970 --> 01:00:30.620
definition this is a, and this
is b, and this is c.

01:00:30.620 --> 01:00:33.910
So these are always by
definition 90 degrees.

01:00:33.910 --> 01:00:36.530
If you use the second setting,
then this is the

01:00:36.530 --> 01:00:38.030
direction of b.

01:00:38.030 --> 01:00:40.220
And this is the direction
of a.

01:00:40.220 --> 01:00:42.940
And this is the direction
of c.

01:00:42.940 --> 01:00:44.800
That keeps the system
right handed.

01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:47.748
Then, this is a right angle and
this is a general angle.

01:00:50.556 --> 01:00:52.428
AUDIENCE: But all you're doing
is taking that top one and

01:00:52.428 --> 01:00:53.840
just [? tilting it over ?].

01:00:53.840 --> 01:00:58.100
PROFESSOR: No, I'm doing more
than that because if there

01:00:58.100 --> 01:01:00.330
were a twofold axis, that would
be the direction of the

01:01:00.330 --> 01:01:01.490
twofold axis.

01:01:01.490 --> 01:01:03.610
Now, this is the direction
of the twofold axis.

01:01:06.330 --> 01:01:08.600
The other thing that happens
is the symbols

01:01:08.600 --> 01:01:10.640
for the glides change.

01:01:10.640 --> 01:01:15.950
So if you look at space group
number seven, which is a case

01:01:15.950 --> 01:01:20.830
where the mirror plane has been
replaced by a b glide in

01:01:20.830 --> 01:01:23.760
the first setting, and that
means the glide is

01:01:23.760 --> 01:01:25.650
perpendicular to the
twofold axis.

01:01:25.650 --> 01:01:31.050
If the twofold axis is now the
direction of b, the glide

01:01:31.050 --> 01:01:32.500
plane turns into a b glide.

01:01:38.410 --> 01:01:40.820
But let's just thumb through
them quickly.

01:01:40.820 --> 01:01:43.780
And then, we're actually two
minutes past my promised

01:01:43.780 --> 01:01:45.370
quitting hour.

01:01:45.370 --> 01:01:47.340
First one, P2.

01:01:47.340 --> 01:01:51.485
Then, replace the twofold access
by a 2 sub 1 screw.

01:01:51.485 --> 01:01:57.190
So that's Schoenflies symbol
C2 superscript 2.

01:01:57.190 --> 01:02:00.275
Then, do this with centered
lattices.

01:02:00.275 --> 01:02:03.170
The international table
chooses to use a

01:02:03.170 --> 01:02:04.900
side centered cell.

01:02:04.900 --> 01:02:07.230
So that's the third one you can
get from a twofold axis.

01:02:07.230 --> 01:02:13.950
So Schoenflies calls it C
subscript 2 superscript 3.

01:02:13.950 --> 01:02:17.860
And if you add that to a side
centered lattice, you get

01:02:17.860 --> 01:02:22.950
screw axes interleaved between
the twofold axes.

01:02:22.950 --> 01:02:27.300
Put it on its side, it stays
C2 superscript 3 in the

01:02:27.300 --> 01:02:29.630
Schoenflies notation.

01:02:29.630 --> 01:02:36.720
But the side centered d become
side centered c because it's b

01:02:36.720 --> 01:02:39.330
that comes out of
the oblique net.

01:02:39.330 --> 01:02:42.470
So the international
symbol tells you

01:02:42.470 --> 01:02:45.140
exactly what you have.

01:02:45.140 --> 01:02:48.080
The Schoenflies symbol
is arbitrary.

01:02:48.080 --> 01:02:50.520
It tells you the point group and
it tells you the order in

01:02:50.520 --> 01:02:52.170
which Schoenflies
derived them.

01:02:52.170 --> 01:02:56.990
But that non-informative
nature to the

01:02:56.990 --> 01:02:58.750
symbol has a blessing.

01:02:58.750 --> 01:03:02.520
And that is it doesn't change
with different labellings of

01:03:02.520 --> 01:03:04.170
a, b, and c.

01:03:04.170 --> 01:03:09.075
It doesn't change with a being
shortest, b being shortest.

01:03:11.760 --> 01:03:14.580
It just sits there and its dumb,
uninformative fashion.

01:03:14.580 --> 01:03:15.770
And that is nice.

01:03:15.770 --> 01:03:17.450
So both of them have survived.

01:03:17.450 --> 01:03:21.910
OK, so could we get another
space group out of this by

01:03:21.910 --> 01:03:24.540
replacing the twofold
axis by a 2 sub 1?

01:03:24.540 --> 01:03:29.060
No, because we've already got
2 sub 1 screw axes in C2

01:03:29.060 --> 01:03:30.420
superscript 3.

01:03:30.420 --> 01:03:35.470
So then, Schoenflies moves on
and begins to work with

01:03:35.470 --> 01:03:36.700
symmetry planes.

01:03:36.700 --> 01:03:40.010
So number six puts a mirror
plane in the primitive

01:03:40.010 --> 01:03:42.690
monoclinic lattice.

01:03:42.690 --> 01:03:44.330
That becomes CS.

01:03:44.330 --> 01:03:47.470
That's the Schoenflies symbol
for point group m.

01:03:47.470 --> 01:03:49.790
And it's the first thing
you can get.

01:03:49.790 --> 01:03:53.820
Another piece of convention
for displaying the

01:03:53.820 --> 01:03:57.650
representative pattern of atoms,
in the first setting,

01:03:57.650 --> 01:04:01.070
the two atoms sit directly
above one another.

01:04:01.070 --> 01:04:02.960
So there are two new
things here.

01:04:02.960 --> 01:04:07.210
A vertical line through the atom
indicates that there are

01:04:07.210 --> 01:04:10.350
two of them that are
superimposed in projection.

01:04:10.350 --> 01:04:14.640
And moreover, the little tadpole
has appeared inside

01:04:14.640 --> 01:04:17.230
the frog eggs in the
left hand part.

01:04:17.230 --> 01:04:20.740
So this says on the right hand
side of that split circle, the

01:04:20.740 --> 01:04:22.900
atom is at plus z.

01:04:22.900 --> 01:04:25.490
On the left hand side with the
comment to indicate an

01:04:25.490 --> 01:04:29.810
enantiomorph is 1 at minus
z that sits directly

01:04:29.810 --> 01:04:31.360
below the first one.

01:04:31.360 --> 01:04:33.210
And you'll notice in the
diagram of the symmetry

01:04:33.210 --> 01:04:36.230
elements is a chevron working
off the lower right hand

01:04:36.230 --> 01:04:37.150
corner of the cell.

01:04:37.150 --> 01:04:39.330
And that's the symbol for a
mirror plane that's being

01:04:39.330 --> 01:04:42.110
viewed directly from above.

01:04:42.110 --> 01:04:43.880
And then I'll just
go a couple more.

01:04:43.880 --> 01:04:48.400
You could replace the mirror
plane with a glide plane.

01:04:48.400 --> 01:04:50.810
And that's a b glide.

01:04:50.810 --> 01:04:54.340
Now, you can see the atoms
going up at plus z, slide

01:04:54.340 --> 01:04:58.550
along by 1/2 z, and popped down
to minus z, going down to

01:04:58.550 --> 01:05:02.630
an enantiomorph, so there's
a comma inside the circle.

01:05:02.630 --> 01:05:06.890
The chevron in the lower right
hand corner of the diagram of

01:05:06.890 --> 01:05:09.990
symmetry elements now has
acquired an arrow, a barb,

01:05:09.990 --> 01:05:14.060
that indicates the
direction of tau.

01:05:14.060 --> 01:05:19.430
The second setting, again, flops
the thing on its side so

01:05:19.430 --> 01:05:23.660
that you're looking now down
along the b glide.

01:05:23.660 --> 01:05:27.240
And so you see a dotted line
that indicates a glide plane

01:05:27.240 --> 01:05:31.070
viewed edge on in the
direction of tau.

01:05:31.070 --> 01:05:34.230
Then, you can put a mirror plane
for number eight into a

01:05:34.230 --> 01:05:36.960
side centered b lattice.

01:05:36.960 --> 01:05:41.870
And that gives you another
space group.

01:05:41.870 --> 01:05:46.520
And then, you can put a glide
plane into the b lattice.

01:05:46.520 --> 01:05:51.180
And that, interestingly, gives
you a different space group.

01:05:53.790 --> 01:05:57.650
Number eight has an alternating
mirror plane with

01:05:57.650 --> 01:06:00.120
an axial glide.

01:06:00.120 --> 01:06:05.680
Number nine has an alternating
axial glide alternating with a

01:06:05.680 --> 01:06:07.690
diagonal glide-- two
glide planes.

01:06:07.690 --> 01:06:09.820
Not a mirror plane and a glide,
but two different kinds

01:06:09.820 --> 01:06:11.180
of glide planes.

01:06:11.180 --> 01:06:14.200
And then, you've used up all the
tricks you can pull there.

01:06:14.200 --> 01:06:18.260
So now, we take the last
monoclinic point group, 2/m,

01:06:18.260 --> 01:06:20.430
drop it into a primitive
lattice.

01:06:20.430 --> 01:06:25.260
Replace the twofold axis with
a 2 sub 1 screw axis.

01:06:25.260 --> 01:06:27.650
That gives you P2
sub 1 over m.

01:06:27.650 --> 01:06:31.450
Then, leave the twofold axis
alone and leave the plane

01:06:31.450 --> 01:06:34.830
alone and put 2/m in a
side centered cell.

01:06:34.830 --> 01:06:39.290
And then, replace the mirror
plane by a glide.

01:06:39.290 --> 01:06:41.610
That's number 13.

01:06:41.610 --> 01:06:48.930
And then finally, the summa cum
ultra, replace the twofold

01:06:48.930 --> 01:06:52.576
axis y a 2 sub 1 screw and
replace the mirror plane with

01:06:52.576 --> 01:06:55.280
a glide, number 14.

01:06:55.280 --> 01:06:59.410
And then, do the same thing
in a centered lattice.

01:06:59.410 --> 01:07:04.600
So we get a total of 13
different space groups from

01:07:04.600 --> 01:07:07.890
two lousy kinds of lattices
and three

01:07:07.890 --> 01:07:09.310
possible point groups.

01:07:09.310 --> 01:07:14.940
You get 13 different distinct
space groups.

01:07:14.940 --> 01:07:16.275
OK, that's a quick overview.

01:07:19.930 --> 01:07:23.140
Notice that just as was the case
for the plane groups, the

01:07:23.140 --> 01:07:28.880
tables go on to list the way in
which atoms are related by

01:07:28.880 --> 01:07:34.370
symmetry and the number per
cell and the site symmetry

01:07:34.370 --> 01:07:36.100
just as in the plane groups.

01:07:36.100 --> 01:07:38.140
And the way a three dimensional
structure is going

01:07:38.140 --> 01:07:41.450
to be described to you is
exactly analogous to what we

01:07:41.450 --> 01:07:43.370
did with two dimensions.

01:07:43.370 --> 01:07:53.930
Magnesium in position 3b,
symmetry 6/m, oxygen in

01:07:53.930 --> 01:07:58.710
position 12d, symmetry 1.

01:07:58.710 --> 01:08:01.730
